    <a href="/reading/category-theory/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>Simple Algebraic Data Types</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2015 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2015/01/13/simple-algebraic-data-types/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 6</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-04/">🍞 Ch. 5</a> (Products and Coproducts). 8 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Types form a <strong>semiring</strong>. Product types are multiplication, sum types are addition, <code>Void</code> is 0, <code>Unit</code> is 1. The same algebraic identities you learned in grade school — <code>a × 1 = a</code>, <code>a + 0 = a</code>, distributivity — hold for types up to isomorphism. A type definition is an equation you can solve.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Product and Sum type algebra -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 420 160" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Product: A x B -->
